          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During axillary surgery, a nerve is inadvertently damaged. Post-operatively, the patient shows visible wasting of the upper chest and cannot flex the arm forward at the shoulder. Which nerve was most likely injured?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Medial pectoral nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The medial pectoral nerve (C8, T1) primarily supplies the sternocostal head. Its injury would impair extension from a flexed position and lower-fibre adduction, not isolated loss of forward flexion.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lateral pectoral nerve</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The lateral pectoral nerve (C5, C6, C7) supplies the clavicular head of pectoralis major, which is responsible for forward flexion of the arm up to 90 degrees.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Long thoracic nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The long thoracic nerve supplies the serratus anterior. Its injury produces winging of the scapula, not wasting of pectoralis major.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Thoracodorsal nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The thoracodorsal nerve supplies the latissimus dorsi. Its injury impairs arm extension and medial rotation from behind, not forward flexion.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The lateral pectoral nerve (C5–C7) supplies the clavicular head of pectoralis major, which flexes the arm forward. Both pectoral nerves must be preserved during axillary surgery to prevent visible wasting."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The lateral pectoral nerve (C5–C7) serves the clavicular head. Since this head flexes the arm forward, its denervation causes both loss of flexion and visible upper-chest wasting."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
