          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>After a mastectomy, a patient develops lymphoedema of the ipsilateral arm. The c</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>After a mastectomy, a patient develops lymphoedema of the ipsilateral arm. The clavipectoral fascia was disrupted during the procedure. Which structure passing through this fascia is most directly responsible for this complication?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cephalic vein</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The cephalic vein passes through the clavipectoral fascia to drain into the axillary vein, but its disruption would impair venous return — not cause lymphoedema.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lateral pectoral nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This nerve passes through the fascia to reach pectoralis major. Its disruption would cause muscle wasting, not lymphoedema.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Pectoral branches of the thoracoacromial artery</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>These arterial branches pass through the fascia to supply the pectoral muscles. Their disruption impairs blood supply, not lymphatic drainage.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Axillary lymphatics</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Lymphatic vessels from the breast pass through the clavipectoral fascia toward the axillary nodes. Disrupting these channels obstructs lymph drainage, directly causing arm lymphoedema.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Axillary lymphatics (the 'A' in LCTA) are the lymph channels from the breast passing through the clavipectoral fascia. When disrupted during mastectomy, lymph drainage is obstructed, causing arm lymphoedema."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The 'A' in the LCTA mnemonic stands for axillary lymphatics — breast lymph channels passing through the clavipectoral fascia. Their disruption during mastectomy is the direct cause of post-operative arm lymphoedema."
                }
              ],
