          "label": "<p>A 48-year-old woman presents with visible skin dimpling over a hard breast lump.</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A 48-year-old woman presents with visible skin dimpling over a hard breast lump. Which anatomical structure must the tumour have invaded to produce this clinical sign?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lactiferous sinuses</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Lactiferous sinuses are dilated portions of the ducts near the nipple. Their invasion may cause nipple discharge, but does not produce skin dimpling.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Retromammary space</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The retromammary space lies between the breast and the deep fascia. Invasion here fixes the breast to the chest wall, limiting its mobility — but does not dimple the overlying skin.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cooper's ligaments</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Cooper's (suspensory) ligaments are fibrous strands running from the deep fascia to the skin. Tumour invasion shortens them, pulling the overlying skin inward — the classic dimple sign.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Myoepithelial cells</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Myoepithelial cells are microscopic contractile cells surrounding the alveoli. They participate in the milk ejection reflex; their invasion does not produce visible skin changes.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Skin dimpling in breast cancer is caused by tumour invasion of Cooper's (suspensory) ligaments. These fibrous strands run from the deep fascia to the skin; when shortened by infiltration, they pull the skin inward."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Cooper's ligaments connect the skin to the deep fascia. When a tumour invades and shortens them, the overlying skin is pulled inward — producing the dimple sign, a key indicator of breast malignancy."
                }
              ],
